sub_title: A Landscape approach to Humanity  -  Design enthusiast  -  double hatted  -  Architect /Landscape Architect
summary:
Architect, landscape architect, designer. Curious when it comes to new ideas…after receiving my master degree in architecture from the National school of Architecture in Tunisia, I continued to earn a master of landscape architecture from TU Delft in the Netherlands.
I had the opportunity to work on various projects in France, Qatar, Ivory Coast, the Netherlands and Jordan. 
Enthusiastic about humanitarian causes through my studies and my work, I am aspiring to participate in shaping a better world.

projects:
[{'title': 'Public space as a vector of connection on the jordanian Syrian border: A park of Sarhan municipality', 'date': {'start': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}, 'end': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}}, 'description': "The Local Government Resilience Program, or LOGOReP, is committed to strengthen the resilience of Lebanese and Jordanian communities whose living conditions and infrastructure are being put under severe pressure by the influx of Syrian refugees.  

Within this program we are working on providing a better public space in the North Jordanian border municipality of Sarhan.  In consultation with administrators, councilors and policy officials of the municipality of Sarhan, a practical design was made for a park with sports and game facilities close to the mosque and to the children's library.  

Trees can grow by terrassing the terrain and storing rainwater.
The park is constructed via the GIZ Cash For Work program.  Led by a local contractor, a team of 15 Jordanians and 15 Syrian refugees will construct the park.  These people will gain experience and grow a network while giving a public space to their community.", 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Amina', 'last_name': 'Mnif', 'name': None, 'headline': 'A Landscape approach to Humanity  -  Design enthusiast  -  double hatted  -  Architect /Landscape Architect'}]}, {'title': 'Strategic development framework for Zaatari refugee Camp in Jordan', 'date': {'start': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}, 'end': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}}, 'description': 'Zaatari camp is a large refugee camp in North Jordan, close to the Syrian border. Together with a team from the Municipality of Amsterdam and commissioned by the VNG International, LODEWIJK BALJON landscape architects drew up a development framework that provides guidance for further urban development.
